{
    "unitNumber": 21,
    "text": {
        "title": "Imperative",
        "sections": [
            {
                "title": "Use of the Imperative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 1,
                        "content": "The **imperative** is used, in Italian as in English, to express **orders**, **commands**, or **strong requests**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Guarda**!", "Look!"],
                                ["**Entrate**!", "Come in!"],
                                ["**Chiedi** a tuo padre.", "Ask your father."],
                                ["**Venga** domani, Signora!", "Come tomorrow, Madam!"],
                                ["**Andiamo**!", "Let’s go!"],
                                ["**Dammi** il libro.", "Give me the book."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "As well as orders and requests, the **imperative** can also be used to express **wishes**, **invitations**, **encouragement**, and **advice**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Passa** delle buone vacanze.", "Have a good holiday."],
                                ["**Ti ascolto**: **dimmi** tutto.", "I’m listening to you: tell me everything."],
                                ["**Non ti preoccupare**.", "Don’t worry."],
                                ["**Hai l’aria stanca**: **vai** a letto!", "You look tired: go to bed!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Forms of the Imperative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 2,
                        "content": "Regular verbs in **-are**, **-ere**, and **-ire** are conjugated as follows:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Parlare (To speak)", "Prendere (To take/get)", "Partire (To leave)"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["tu", "parla", "prendi", "parti"],
                                ["Lei", "parli", "prenda", "parta"],
                                ["noi", "parliamo", "prendiamo", "partiamo"],
                                ["voi", "parlate", "prendete", "partite"],
                                ["Loro", "parlino", "prendano", "partano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Some verbs ending in **-ire** add **-isc-**, as in the **present indicative** (see Unit 5):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Finire (To finish)", "Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["tu", "finisci", "finish"],
                                ["Lei", "finisca", "finish"],
                                ["noi", "finiamo", "let us finish"],
                                ["voi", "finite", "finish"],
                                ["Loro", "finiscano", "finish"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "In the **first person plural**, the meaning is more that of a **suggestion** than an order, made to a group of which we are part (cf. the English ‘Let’s have a coffee’). The **third person singular and plural** forms (**Lei** and **Loro**) are used for **formal address**."
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Irregular Imperatives",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 3,
                        "content": "Some verbs have irregular forms in the **tu** imperative. The most important are:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Verb", "tu Imperative", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["andare", "va’", "go"],
                                ["dare", "da’", "give"],
                                ["dire", "di’", "say/tell"],
                                ["fare", "fa’", "do/make"],
                                ["stare", "sta’", "stay/be"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Va’** a casa!", "Go home!"],
                                ["**Da’** un po’ di latte al gatto.", "Give some milk to the cat."],
                                ["**Di’** la verità.", "Tell the truth."],
                                ["**Fa’** i compiti!", "Do your homework!"],
                                ["**Sta’** zitto!", "Be quiet!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Other forms of these verbs are regular, except for **dire** in the **Loro** form (**dicano**).",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Andare", "Dare", "Dire", "Fare", "Stare"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["Lei", "vada", "dia", "dica", "faccia", "stia"],
                                ["noi", "andiamo", "diamo", "diciamo", "facciamo", "stiamo"],
                                ["voi", "andate", "date", "dite", "fate", "state"],
                                ["Loro", "vadano", "diano", "dicano", "facciano", "stiano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Negative Imperative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 7,
                        "content": "The **negative imperative** for the **tu** form is formed by placing **non** before the **infinitive** of the verb. For all other forms (**Lei**, **noi**, **voi**, **Loro**), **non** is simply placed before the **imperative**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Parlare", "Prendere", "Partire"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["tu", "non parlare", "non prendere", "non partire"],
                                ["Lei", "non parli", "non prenda", "non parta"],
                                ["noi", "non parliamo", "non prendiamo", "non partiamo"],
                                ["voi", "non parlate", "non prendete", "non partite"],
                                ["Loro", "non parlino", "non prendano", "non partano"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Non parlare** così!", "Don’t talk like that!"],
                                ["**Non prendere** quel libro!", "Don’t take that book!"],
                                ["**Non partiamo** adesso.", "Let’s not leave now."],
                                ["**Non parta** ancora, Signora!", "Don’t leave yet, Madam!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Imperative with Pronouns",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 10,
                        "content": "When an **unstressed pronoun** (direct, indirect, reflexive, **ne**, **ci**) is used with the **imperative**, the pronoun is **always attached** to the verb if it is in a **second person** form (**tu** or **voi**) or the **first person plural** form (**noi**):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["Quel libro è per te: **prendilo**.", "That book is for you: take it."],
                                ["**Chiediamole** aiuto.", "Let’s ask her for help."],
                                ["Se hai dei problemi, **parlane**.", "If you are having problems, talk about them."],
                                ["**Alzatevi**, ragazzi!", "Get up, boys!"],
                                ["**Telefonagli** (or **Telefona loro** – see Unit 10, paragraph 2).", "Phone them."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Note that when an **unstressed pronoun** is used with the forms **da’**, **fa’**, **di’**, **sta’**, and **va’**, the first consonant of the pronoun (except **gli**) is **doubled**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["Se sai la verità, **dilla**!", "If you know the truth, tell it!"],
                                ["**Dammi** la penna!", "Give me the pen!"],
                                ["**Danne** un po’ a tuo fratello.", "Give some to your brother."],
                                ["**Fammi** un piacere.", "Do me a favour."],
                                ["**Vallo** a comprare!", "Go and buy it!"],
                                ["**Vacci** subito.", "Go there at once."],
                                ["**Dille** la verità.", "Tell her the truth."],
                                ["**Digli** la verità.", "Tell him the truth."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "In **negative sentences**, there is an **extra option**: the pronoun can be placed **before the verb** (and after **non**):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Non lo prendere**! or **Non prenderlo**!", "Don’t take it!"],
                                ["**Non le chiediamo** aiuto. or **Non chiediamole** aiuto.", "Let’s not ask her for help."],
                                ["**Non ne parlare**! or **Non parlarne**!", "Don’t talk about it!"],
                                ["**Non vi alzate**! or **Non alzatevi**!", "Don’t get up!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 11,
                        "content": "In the **polite form** (**third person singular and plural**, **Lei** and **Loro**), the pronouns are **always placed before the verb**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["Quel libro è per Lei: **lo prenda**.", "That book is for you: take it."],
                                ["**Le scriva** una mail.", "Write her an email."],
                                ["**Ne parlino** al controllore.", "Speak to the conductor about it."],
                                ["**Si alzi**, Signora!", "Get up, Madam!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    "exercises": [
        {
            "title": "Exercise 1: Supply Imperative",
            "instruction": "Supply the **imperative** of the verb in brackets.",
            "examples": [
                "(**tu comprare**) il pane.: **Compra** il pane.",
                "(**noi uscire**) subito.: **Usciamo** subito."
            ],
            "items": [
                { "question": "(**tu comprare**) il pane.", "answer": "Compra il pane." },
                { "question": "(**noi uscire**) subito.", "answer": "Usciamo subito." },
                { "question": "(**Lei stare**) tranquilla, Signora!", "answer": "Stia tranquilla, Signora!" },
                { "question": "(**tu mettere**) in ordine!", "answer": "Metti in ordine!" },
                { "question": "(**voi essere**) gentili.", "answer": "Siate gentili." },
                { "question": "(**Lei venire**), Professore!", "answer": "Venga, Professore!" },
                { "question": "(**tu dare**) una mano a tuo fratello.", "answer": "Da’ una mano a tuo fratello." },
                { "question": "(**tu finire**) i compiti.", "answer": "Finisci i compiti." },
                { "question": "(**comprare**) questa borsa, Signora!", "answer": "Compri questa borsa, Signora!" },
                { "question": "(**noi fare**) una pausa!", "answer": "Facciamo una pausa!" },
                { "question": "(**tu avere**) fiducia in lei.", "answer": "Abbi fiducia in lei." },
                { "question": "(**Lei parlare**) più forte, Signora.", "answer": "Parli più forte, Signora." },
                { "question": "(**tu andare**) fuori!", "answer": "Va’ fuori!" },
                { "question": "(**tu dire**) tutto quello che sai.", "answer": "Di’ tutto quello che sai." },
                { "question": "(**Lei fare**) attenzione, Signora.", "answer": "Faccia attenzione, Signora." },
                { "question": "(**voi scrivere**) le cartoline!", "answer": "Scrivete le cartoline!" },
                { "question": "(**tu fare**) attenzione!", "answer": "Fa’ attenzione!" },
                { "question": "(**Loro entrare**), Signori.", "answer": "Entrino, Signori." },
                { "question": "(**voi aprire**) le finestre!", "answer": "Aprite le finestre!" },
                { "question": "(**tu rispondere**) al telefono.", "answer": "Rispondi al telefono." }
            ]
        },
        {
